00:21:23,783 --> 00:21:25,850
  -Would you like to join us?   

209
00:21:25,852 --> 00:21:27,018
    -I can't at the moment.     

210
00:21:27,020 --> 00:21:28,719
      My research keeps me      
         busy at night.         

211
00:21:28,721 --> 00:21:31,088
     -What kind of research     
           do you do?           

212
00:21:31,090 --> 00:21:33,924
   -I'm cataloging nocturnal    
          animal life           

213
00:21:33,926 --> 00:21:35,493
      unique to this area.      

214
00:21:35,495 --> 00:21:38,763
I'm afraid it's a rather boring 
    subject to most people.     

215
00:21:38,765 --> 00:21:39,730
          -Oh, no, no.          

216
00:21:39,732 --> 00:21:41,132
           Not to us.           

217
00:21:41,134 --> 00:21:42,533
Um, we're studying the folklore 
       of the region, and       

218
00:21:42,535 --> 00:21:45,736
      animals often figure      
         in folktales.          

219
00:21:45,738 --> 00:21:47,738
     Please, tell us more.      

220
00:21:47,740 --> 00:21:50,708
    -Another time, perhaps.     

221
00:21:50,710 --> 00:21:51,809
           I must go.           

222
00:21:51,811 --> 00:21:53,210
            Ladies.             

223
00:21:56,783 --> 00:21:59,183
     -Animals often figure      
          in folklore.          

224
00:21:59,185 --> 00:22:02,720
     Please, tell us more.      

225
00:22:02,722 --> 00:22:04,121
         -Knock it off.         

226
00:22:15,668 --> 00:22:19,036
    -Hey, wait up, you guys.    

227
00:22:19,038 --> 00:22:22,039
      Let's rest a minute.      

228
00:22:22,041 --> 00:22:27,278
   -Not yet, in just a little   
   bit farther up this hill.    

229
00:22:27,280 --> 00:22:28,212
   MICHELLE: Five   
     interviews in one day.     

230
00:22:28,214 --> 00:22:29,647
     Not a bad start, huh?      

231
00:22:29,649 --> 00:22:31,749
MARA: And this could
      be the best one yet.      

232
00:22:31,751 --> 00:22:33,451
 This old lady is very strange. 

233
00:22:42,895 --> 00:22:45,596
  This is the mask you wear at  
  the festival of the undead?   

234
00:22:48,134 --> 00:22:52,103
     -It's likeness of the      
       gypsy who made the       

235
00:22:52,105 --> 00:22:53,504
    truce with the vampires.    

236
00:22:57,744 --> 00:23:07,752
  Wear the mask and I tell you  
    the story of the gypsy.     

237
00:23:07,754 --> 00:23:12,156
 The vampires killed the Turks. 

238
00:23:12,158 --> 00:23:18,863
  And in gratitude, the people  
 said, let them have the great  

239
00:23:18,865 --> 00:23:24,368
     ruins, which is where      
      the vampires sleep.       

240
00:23:24,370 --> 00:23:28,339
       The vampires were        
         still hungry.          

241
00:23:28,341 --> 00:23:31,876
      They would come out       
       of their wings at        

242
00:23:31,878 --> 00:23:35,246
     night and drink blood.     

243
00:23:38,384 --> 00:23:46,123
  This gypsy, he knew that the  
 pope of Rome had a stone which 

244
00:23:46,125 --> 00:23:49,427
      dripped the blood of      
        all the saints.         

245
00:23:49,429 --> 00:24:02,006
 So she went to Rome, stole the 
 stone, and took it to the king 

246
